## PHASE 3.3 вЂ” All API Endpoints

### USERS ROUTES (routes/users.py) вЂ” prefix: /api/users

GET    /api/users              - List all users, support query params: role, department, is_active, search (searches first_name, last_name, email, badge_id), skip=0, limit=20
POST   /api/users              - Create new user, validate badge_id uniqueness, validate email uniqueness
PUT    /api/users/{id}         - Update user fields (any subset)
DELETE /api/users/{id}         - Soft delete: set is_active=False, never delete the record


### ACCESS ROUTES (routes/access.py) вЂ” prefix: /api/access

POST /api/access/request       - THE MAIN ENDPOINT (most critical):
  Request body: { badge_id, access_point_id, timestamp }
  Logic:
    1. Look up user by badge_id в†’ if not found return decision=denied, reason="unknown_badge"
    2. Check user is_active в†’ if False return decision=denied, reason="deactivated_user"
    3. Look up access_point by id в†’ if not found or status != active return decision=denied
    4. Check required_clearance vs user clearance_level в†’ if insufficient return decision=denied
    5. Extract contextual features:
       - hour = timestamp.hour
       - day_of_week = timestamp.weekday() (0=Monday)
       - is_weekend = day_of_week >= 5
       - access_frequency_24h = count of this user's logs in last 24 hours
       - time_since_last_access_min = minutes since user's last access log
       - location_match = check if access_point.zone matches user department zone mapping
       - role_level = map role to int (employee=1, manager=2, admin=3, security=2, contractor=1, visitor=1)
       - is_restricted_area = access_point.is_restricted
    6. For now use RULE-BASED risk scoring (ML will replace this in Phase 4):
       - Start with risk_score = 0.0
       - If hour < 6 or hour > 22: risk_score += 0.35
       - If is_weekend and role not in (admin, security): risk_score += 0.20
       - If not location_match: risk_score += 0.20
       - If is_restricted_area and user.clearance_level < 4: risk_score += 0.30
       - If access_frequency_24h > 10: risk_score += 0.25
       - If time_since_last_access_min is not None and time_since_last_access_min < 5: risk_score += 0.30
       - Cap risk_score at 1.0
    7. Apply decision thresholds from config:
       - risk_score < 0.3 в†’ decision = granted
       - risk_score 0.3 to 0.7 в†’ decision = delayed
       - risk_score >= 0.7 в†’ decision = denied
    8. Save access_log with all feature columns
    9. If decision is denied or delayed and risk_score >= 0.5: create anomaly_alert
       - alert_type based on which rule triggered highest score
    10. Return: { decision, risk_score, log_id, reason }

GET /api/access/logs           - List access logs, filter by: user_id, access_point_id, decision, date_from, date_to, skip=0, limit=20. Return with user name and access point name joined.
GET /api/access/logs/{id}      - Get single log with full details


### ALERTS ROUTES (routes/alerts.py) вЂ” prefix: /api/alerts

GET /api/alerts                - List alerts, filter by: severity, status, date_from, date_to, skip=0, limit=20. Include user info and access point name.
GET /api/alerts/{id}           - Get single alert details
PUT /api/alerts/{id}/resolve   - Mark alert as resolved: set status=resolved, is_resolved=True, resolved_at=now(), resolved_by=user_id from request body


### STATS ROUTES (routes/stats.py) вЂ” prefix: /api/stats

GET /api/stats/overview        - Return: { total_accesses_today, denied_today, delayed_today, active_alerts_count, total_users, total_access_points }
GET /api/stats/access-timeline - Return hourly access counts for last 24 hours: [ { hour, granted, denied, delayed } ]
GET /api/stats/anomaly-distribution - Return alert counts grouped by severity: [ { severity, count } ]
GET /api/stats/top-access-points    - Return top 5 most used access points today: [ { name, building, total, granted, denied } ]


